1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,708
We are starting on a red checkout failure in Quorvex Demo Shop.

2
00:00:02,708 --> 00:00:05,501
The generated Playwright run did not pass, and that is the point.

3
00:00:05,501 --> 00:00:07,951
Here we have a commerce project called Quorvex Demo Shop.

4
00:00:07,951 --> 00:00:11,433
The dashboard already tells us the release is risky: failed checkout tests, flaky

5
00:00:11,433 --> 00:00:14,957
state restoration, a slow checkout retry, and a database quality run with customer

6
00:00:14,957 --> 00:00:15,688
and order issues.

7
00:00:15,688 --> 00:00:17,966
Most demo videos start with a perfect generated test.

8
00:00:17,966 --> 00:00:19,556
Real QA work does not look like that.

9
00:00:19,556 --> 00:00:23,123
Real QA work starts when generated tests fail, selectors drift, validation changes,

10
00:00:23,123 --> 00:00:26,347
the database disagrees with the UI, and someone has to decide what matters.

11
00:00:26,347 --> 00:00:29,613
This walkthrough shows how Quorvex AI turns those failures into organized QA

12
00:00:29,613 --> 00:00:30,000
evidence.

13
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:35,134
AI-generated tests and QA agents are useful, but they are not magic.

14
00:00:35,134 --> 00:00:37,777
They can produce brittle selectors.

15
00:00:37,777 --> 00:00:42,081
They can expose a real bug and still need a human review.

16
00:00:42,081 --> 00:00:48,196
They can fail because the application changed, or because the generated assertion

17
00:00:48,196 --> 00:00:48,951
was wrong.

18
00:00:48,951 --> 00:00:54,916
The useful system is not the one that pretends every generated test is perfect.

19
00:00:54,916 --> 00:00:59,748
The useful system is the one that keeps the failure explainable.

20
00:00:59,748 --> 00:01:06,091
For a QA team, that means you need specs, historical runs, logs, failure categories,

21
00:01:06,091 --> 00:01:12,433
agent findings, generated test ideas, and enough evidence to decide the next action.

22
00:01:12,433 --> 00:01:15,000
That is the workflow in this demo.

23
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:22,651
I am starting from the project selector and choosing Quorvex Demo Shop.

24
00:01:22,651 --> 00:01:29,763
This project is seeded for the demo, so the data is deterministic.

25
00:01:29,763 --> 00:01:38,060
I am not depending on a live agent run behaving perfectly during a recording.

26
00:01:38,060 --> 00:01:46,789
The point is to show the workflow clearly: what a QA engineer sees after checkout

27
00:01:46,789 --> 00:01:53,362
coverage has been generated and a nightly run found problems.

28
00:01:53,362 --> 00:02:02,091
The specs cover login, cart pricing, discount codes, payment validation, checkout

29
00:02:02,091 --> 00:02:05,323
state, and order confirmation.

30
00:02:05,323 --> 00:02:14,267
The run history includes passed tests, failed tests, a healed checkout run, a flaky

31
00:02:14,267 --> 00:02:18,578
checkout-state case, and a slow timeout.

32
00:02:18,578 --> 00:02:27,414
That gives us enough signal to talk like a real QA review instead of just clicking

33
00:02:27,414 --> 00:02:30,000
through a platform tour.

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,801
Now I will open the failed run for checkout payment validation.

35
00:02:34,801 --> 00:02:37,544
The first failure is selector drift.

36
00:02:37,544 --> 00:02:43,641
The test was looking for a Pay now button, but the current page has a hidden old

37
00:02:43,641 --> 00:02:48,442
button and a visible submit control with a more stable test id.

38
00:02:48,442 --> 00:02:51,338
That is not the same as a product bug.

39
00:02:51,338 --> 00:02:53,548
It is automation maintenance.

40
00:02:53,548 --> 00:02:59,111
The run details show the stage, the failure reason, and the log evidence.

41
00:02:59,111 --> 00:03:05,284
A QA engineer can fix the locator or ask Quorvex to generate a revised Playwright

42
00:03:05,284 --> 00:03:07,113
test from the same spec.

43
00:03:07,113 --> 00:03:11,990
The next failure is more serious: payment validation regression.

44
00:03:11,990 --> 00:03:17,401
The test expected an expired card to be blocked with an inline message.

45
00:03:17,401 --> 00:03:20,754
Instead, the page showed payment authorized.

46
00:03:20,754 --> 00:03:23,268
That looks like a product defect.

47
00:03:23,268 --> 00:03:25,021
The difference matters.

48
00:03:25,021 --> 00:03:27,612
Quorvex is not just saying failed.

49
00:03:27,612 --> 00:03:33,937
It is separating selector drift from a validation regression, so the team can route

50
00:03:33,937 --> 00:03:35,385
the work correctly.

51
00:03:35,385 --> 00:03:41,406
I also have a cart total mismatch: expected 86 dollars and 40 cents, but the UI

52
00:03:41,406 --> 00:03:45,064
showed 91 dollars and 40 cents after a discount.

53
00:03:45,064 --> 00:03:49,026
That points to pricing logic or duplicated shipping.

54
00:03:49,026 --> 00:03:53,370
Finally, there is a checkout-state timeout after refresh.

55
00:03:53,370 --> 00:03:59,314
That one is marked flaky because historical runs show both passing and failing

56
00:03:59,314 --> 00:04:00,000
outcomes.

57
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:05,942
Now I will open the agent run called Checkout Failure Triage.

58
00:04:05,942 --> 00:04:11,981
This is a completed report, not a live agent performance demo.

59
00:04:11,981 --> 00:04:19,675
It shows what I want from an agent after a failed run: findings, evidence, test

60
00:04:19,675 --> 00:04:22,500
ideas, and follow-up actions.

61
00:04:22,500 --> 00:04:30,390
The first finding says the payment button locator drifted after a copy and layout

62
00:04:30,390 --> 00:04:31,071
change.

63
00:04:31,071 --> 00:04:38,864
The evidence points to the failed run log where the locator resolved to a hidden

64
00:04:38,864 --> 00:04:39,643
element.

65
00:04:39,643 --> 00:04:47,143
The second finding is the important one: expired card validation allows order

66
00:04:47,143 --> 00:04:48,214
submission.

67
00:04:48,214 --> 00:04:56,299
The evidence says the expected inline error was absent and the run captured Payment

68
00:04:56,299 --> 00:04:57,857
authorized text.

69
00:04:57,857 --> 00:05:03,604
The third finding connects the UI mismatch to cart pricing.

70
00:05:03,604 --> 00:05:08,766
The frontend total diverges from the pricing preview.

71
00:05:08,766 --> 00:05:12,760
From here, the test ideas are actionable.

72
00:05:12,760 --> 00:05:20,065
One suggestion is to add an API-backed cart total contract before checkout.

73
00:05:20,065 --> 00:05:27,857
Another is to retry checkout after an expired session and make sure the customer

74
00:05:27,857 --> 00:05:31,558
returns to the original checkout path.

75
00:05:31,558 --> 00:05:35,162
This is the value of the agent layer.

76
00:05:35,162 --> 00:05:38,377
It does not replace QA ownership.

77
00:05:38,377 --> 00:05:45,000
It collects context and proposes work that a QA engineer can review.

78
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,312
Next I will open the specs.

79
00:05:47,312 --> 00:05:52,962
The checkout payment validation spec is written in plain markdown.

80
00:05:52,962 --> 00:05:59,726
It says what the user does, what data is used, and what the expected result is.

81
00:05:59,726 --> 00:06:06,832
This is important because the generated Playwright code should be traceable back to

82
00:06:06,832 --> 00:06:11,284
the requirement, not just appear as a random script.

83
00:06:11,284 --> 00:06:18,305
The cart total spec describes the exact pricing expectation: line items, discount,

84
00:06:18,305 --> 00:06:20,445
tax, shipping, and total.

85
00:06:20,445 --> 00:06:23,784
That makes the failed assertion useful.

86
00:06:23,784 --> 00:06:30,719
We can tell whether the test is wrong, the UI is wrong, or the backend preview is

87
00:06:30,719 --> 00:06:31,233
wrong.

88
00:06:31,233 --> 00:06:38,253
The login recovery and checkout state specs cover edge cases that are easy to miss

89
00:06:38,253 --> 00:06:40,051
in a happy-path demo.

90
00:06:40,051 --> 00:06:46,729
Session expiry and page refresh are exactly where checkout flows become flaky.

91
00:06:46,729 --> 00:06:50,839
The generated tests are not the source of truth.

92
00:06:50,839 --> 00:06:53,836
The specs are the source of intent.

93
00:06:53,836 --> 00:07:00,000
The tests are executable coverage that should evolve as the app changes.

94
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,805
Now I will switch to database testing.

95
00:07:03,805 --> 00:07:07,911
This is not a full database-testing tour.

96
00:07:07,911 --> 00:07:14,319
I just want to show why UI failures often need backend evidence.

97
00:07:14,319 --> 00:07:19,626
The demo database run has passing and failing checks.

98
00:07:19,626 --> 00:07:27,136
It catches duplicate customers, invalid email format, a negative order item

99
00:07:27,136 --> 00:07:33,745
quantity, and a payment total that does not match the order total.

100
00:07:33,745 --> 00:07:38,752
Those issues connect directly to checkout quality.

101
00:07:38,752 --> 00:07:46,762
If a payment run fails in the browser, and the database also shows order/payment

102
00:07:46,762 --> 00:07:50,968
mismatches, the QA story becomes stronger.

103
00:07:50,968 --> 00:07:59,079
The dashboard then gives the broader signal: pass/fail trend, failure categories,

104
00:07:59,079 --> 00:08:02,183
flaky tests, and slowest tests.

105
00:08:02,183 --> 00:08:10,093
A QA lead can decide whether the release risk is mostly automation maintenance,

106
00:08:10,093 --> 00:08:15,000
product regression, data quality, or performance.

107
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,018
Here is the workflow again.

108
00:08:18,018 --> 00:08:22,265
We started with failed checkout tests.

109
00:08:22,265 --> 00:08:30,425
We inspected a specific failure and separated selector drift from product

110
00:08:30,425 --> 00:08:31,654
regression.

111
00:08:31,654 --> 00:08:40,373
We reviewed an agent report with findings, evidence, test ideas, and follow-up

112
00:08:40,373 --> 00:08:41,267
actions.

113
00:08:41,267 --> 00:08:46,632
We connected specs to generated Playwright work.

114
00:08:46,632 --> 00:08:55,127
Then we looked at database and dashboard signals to understand release risk.

115
00:08:55,127 --> 00:09:03,957
That is the shape of Quorvex AI: generate and organize Playwright QA work, keep

116
00:09:03,957 --> 00:09:09,322
evidence attached, and make failures reviewable.

117
00:09:09,322 --> 00:09:12,116
Teams still own the code.

118
00:09:12,116 --> 00:09:16,140
Teams still decide what should ship.

119
00:09:16,140 --> 00:09:24,747
Quorvex helps collect the context faster and keeps the work from turning into

120
00:09:24,747 --> 00:09:30,000
scattered logs, screenshots, and chat messages.

121
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:38,344
If you want to try this exact demo, seed the project with make youtube-demo-seed and

122
00:09:38,344 --> 00:09:40,629
open Quorvex Demo Shop.

123
00:09:40,629 --> 00:09:48,874
Star the repo if this workflow is useful, and comment with the QA workflow you want

124
00:09:48,874 --> 00:09:56,225
next: API contract testing, PR test selection, database quality checks, or

125
00:09:56,225 --> 00:10:00,000
agent-assisted Playwright maintenance.
